"/>  That was my point with saying &quot;at that point, it's not a problem.&quot;
Obviously, a piece that has encrusted mineral deposits is not
very salable.
&quot;Bloom&quot;, however, means something very different to me, being
that the glass has absorbed the minerals and is now cloudy.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Is this not the case with all glass? And how would one determine
&gt;the inside of a 'bloomed' example was reploished? is there some
&gt;tell-tale sign one can look for?

"/> Ronnie, my friend is a collector of cut glass, and she once showed
me a piece that she'd purchased. She had been seeking a mate to
a vase, so that she could display the pair on her fireplace mantle.

She handed me one and said &quot;Do you see anything odd?&quot;
Not being a fan of such (and frankly, having limited knowledge),
I looked carefully and told her I thought it was a beautiful piece.
She then handed me the other. It was much shinier inside, and
looked a bit more &quot;clear&quot; when you held both of them up to the
light.
What she told me is that she'd purchased it at a very good price
at an antique show, and the dealer told her that it was priced
low because it had been repolished. (My friend is very picky,
knew the dealer well, was a good customer, and the dealer was
always honest with her.) The piece, on its own, looked fabulous.
When she took it home, she could see the differences.

She was happy with her purchase, as where she displayed the
pair, you could not tell the difference. You could, however,
tell the difference when you held both up to the light together.

Kris

